TY  - JOUR
T1  - Difference Equations in Forecasting Formulas
AU  - Brenner, J. L.
AU  - D'Esopo, D. A.
AU  - Fowler, A. G.
Y1  - 1968/11/01
PY  - 1968
DA  - 1968/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.15.3.141
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.15.3.141
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 141
EP  - 159
VL  - 15
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The deviation of actual sales (or other time-dependent statistics) from a model of sales will give rise to forecasting errors that are enhanced, damped out, or shifted in phase, depending on the particular formulas that are used for forecasting. Following R. G. Brown, P. Winters, and Theil, Nerlove, and Wage, we start from a general set of forecasting formulas, but make fewer assumptions than those authors about deviations from the model, and obtain a more extensive collection of results. In particular, we show how to treat errors not serially uncorrelated, and how to investigate forecasting formulas of order higher than second.
AB  - The deviation of actual sales (or other time-dependent statistics) from a model of sales will give rise to forecasting errors that are enhanced, damped out, or shifted in phase, depending on the particular formulas that are used for forecasting. Following R. G. Brown, P. Winters, and Theil, Nerlove, and Wage, we start from a general set of forecasting formulas, but make fewer assumptions than those authors about deviations from the model, and obtain a more extensive collection of results. In particular, we show how to treat errors not serially uncorrelated, and how to investigate forecasting formulas of order higher than second.
